## 1 Â· Sequences

<definition title="Convergent Sequence">
A sequence <m>(a_n)_{n=1}^{\infty}</m> in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> **converges** to
a limit <m>L \in \mathbb{R}</m> if

<math number="true" label="eq:convergence">
\forall\, \varepsilon > 0,\; \exists\, N \in \mathbb{N} :
  n \geq N \implies |a_n - L| < \varepsilon
</math>

We write <m>\lim_{n \to \infty} a_n = L</m> or <m>a_n \to L</m>.
</definition>

<tip title="Intuition">
Think of convergence as: *no matter how small a neighbourhood you draw around
<m>L</m>, the sequence eventually stays inside it forever.*
</tip>

### Key Theorems

<accordion>
  <item title="Squeeze Theorem">

If <m>a_n \leq b_n \leq c_n</m> for all sufficiently large <m>n</m>, and
<m>a_n \to L</m> and <m>c_n \to L</m>, then <m>b_n \to L</m>.

**Proof sketch:** Given <m>\varepsilon > 0</m>, choose <m>N</m> large enough
that both <m>|a_n - L| < \varepsilon</m> and <m>|c_n - L| < \varepsilon</m>.
Then:

<math>
L - \varepsilon < a_n \leq b_n \leq c_n < L + \varepsilon
</math>

So <m>|b_n - L| < \varepsilon</m>. <m>\square</m>

  </item>
  <item title="Monotone Convergence Theorem">

Every bounded monotone sequence converges.

- If <m>(a_n)</m> is **increasing** and bounded above, it converges to
  <m>\sup\{a_n\}</m>.
- If <m>(a_n)</m> is **decreasing** and bounded below, it converges to
  <m>\inf\{a_n\}</m>.

  </item>
  <item title="Bolzanoâ€“Weierstrass Theorem">

Every bounded sequence in <m>\mathbb{R}</m> has a convergent subsequence.

**Proof idea:** Bisect <m>[a, b]</m> containing all terms; one half contains
infinitely many terms. Repeat inductively to extract a Cauchy subsequence.

  </item>
</accordion>

---

## 2 Â· Series

<definition title="Convergence of a Series">
The series <m>\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} a_k</m> **converges** if the sequence of
partial sums <m>S_n = \sum_{k=1}^{n} a_k</m> converges. Its value is:

<math number="true" label="eq:series">
\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} a_k = \lim_{n \to \infty} S_n
</math>
</definition>

### Convergence Tests

<tabs>
  <tab title="Ratio Test">

For a series <m>\sum a_k</m> with positive terms, let

<math>
L = \lim_{n \to \infty} \frac{a_{n+1}}{a_n}
</math>

- <m>L < 1</m> â†’ **converges absolutely**
- <m>L > 1</m> â†’ **diverges**
- <m>L = 1</m> â†’ **inconclusive**

**Example:** For <m>\sum \frac{n!}{n^n}</m>, Stirling gives <m>L = 1/e < 1</m>,
so it converges.

  </tab>
  <tab title="Integral Test">

If <m>f</m> is continuous, positive, and **decreasing** on <m>[1, \infty)</m>
with <m>f(n) = a_n</m>, then:

<math>
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} a_n \text{ converges} \iff \int_1^{\infty} f(x)\,dx
\text{ converges}
</math>

**Example:** <m>\sum 1/n^p</m> converges iff <m>p > 1</m> (p-series).

  </tab>
  <tab title="Comparison Test">

If <m>0 \leq a_n \leq b_n</m> for all large <m>n</m>:

- <m>\sum b_n</m> converges <m>\implies \sum a_n</m> converges
- <m>\sum a_n</m> diverges <m>\implies \sum b_n</m> diverges

**Limit comparison:** If <m>\lim a_n / b_n = c \in (0, \infty)</m>,
then <m>\sum a_n</m> and <m>\sum b_n</m> have the same convergence behaviour.

  </tab>
  <tab title="Alternating Series Test">

If <m>(a_n)</m> is **positive**, **decreasing**, and <m>a_n \to 0</m>, then

<math>
\sum_{n=1}^{\infty} (-1)^{n+1} a_n
</math>

converges (Leibniz criterion). The error after <m>N</m> terms is bounded by
<m>|a_{N+1}|</m>.

  </tab>
</tabs>

