## 5 Â· Flashcard Review

<flashcard>
  <front>
  State the **definition of a Cauchy sequence**.
  </front>
  <back>

  A sequence <m>(a_n)</m> is **Cauchy** if

  <math>
  \forall\, \varepsilon > 0,\; \exists\, N \in \mathbb{N} :
    m, n \geq N \implies |a_m - a_n| < \varepsilon
  </math>

  In <m>\mathbb{R}</m>, Cauchy â†” convergent (completeness).
  </back>
</flashcard>

<flashcard>
  <front>
  When does the geometric series <m>\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} r^n</m> converge,
  and what is its sum?
  </front>
  <back>

  It converges if and only if <m>|r| < 1</m>, with sum:

  <math>
  \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} r^n = \frac{1}{1 - r}
  </math>

  Diverges for <m>|r| \geq 1</m>.
  </back>
</flashcard>

<flashcard>
  <front>
  State the **necessary condition** for series convergence.
  </front>
  <back>

  If <m>\sum a_n</m> converges, then <m>a_n \to 0</m>.

  **Contrapositive (divergence test):** If <m>a_n \not\to 0</m>, the series diverges.

  <warning>
  The converse is **false**. The harmonic series <m>\sum 1/n</m> diverges even
  though <m>1/n \to 0</m>.
  </warning>
  </back>
</flashcard>

