## 6 Â· Self-Assessment

<mcq title="Which test is most efficient for \(\sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n!}{2^n}\)?">
  <option>Integral Test</option>
  <option correct="true">Ratio Test</option>
  <option>Comparison Test</option>
  <option>Alternating Series Test</option>
  <explanation>

  The Ratio Test gives <m>L = \lim n!/2^n \cdot 2^{n+1}/(n+1)! = 2/(n+1) \to 0 < 1</m>,
  so the series converges absolutely. Factorial growth makes the Ratio Test ideal.

  </explanation>
</mcq>

<mcq title="The series \(\sum (-1)^n / \sqrt{n}\) converges by:">
  <option>Ratio Test (conclusive)</option>
  <option>Comparison with \(\sum 1/n\)</option>
  <option correct="true">Alternating Series Test</option>
  <option>It diverges</option>
  <explanation>

  <m>b_n = 1/\sqrt{n}</m> is positive, decreasing, and <m>\to 0</m>.
  By the Leibniz criterion the alternating series converges.
  Note it is **conditionally** convergent (not absolutely, since <m>\sum 1/\sqrt{n}</m>
  diverges as a p-series with <m>p = 1/2 < 1</m>).

  </explanation>
</mcq>

